 :itonami.blueprint/implemented-slice
 "MarketEntry-LLM Advisor ⊣ Market-Entry Compliance Governor, a REAL
 compiled `kotoba-lang/langgraph` StateGraph (`:intake -> :advise ->
 :govern -> :decide -+-> :commit / :request-approval -> :commit /
 :hold`), append-only audit ledger. Turkmenistan's own genuinely thin,
 low-transparency public record supported only THREE independently-
 grounded, differently-confidence-rated facts this iteration (Ministry
 of Justice business registration -- moderate confidence; the 2014 Law
 on Tenders public-procurement legal framework -- high confidence, the
 strongest fact; State Tax Service hususy salgyt belgisi (HSB) tax
 registration -- lower confidence, expat/freelancer tax-advisory blogs
 only), so the governor is FIVE HARD violation functions (spec-basis,
 evidence-incomplete over the three-item checklist, engagement-fee
 recompute, double-draft guard, double-submit guard) -- below every
 other sibling actor built so far in this fleet (AGO=7, LBY/GNB/SDN=6)
 -- deliberately with NO additional flagship conditional check, because
 none of the three facts is specific enough to support one without
 fabricating implied institutional detail (no dedicated procurement
 regulator, no e-procurement portal, no FDI-screening body, no precise
 tax-authority name were independently verified). `:filing/draft` and
 `:filing/submit` (real portal actuation) never auto-commit in any
 phase; `interrupt-before #{:request-approval}` pauses escalated
 requests for real human sign-off via a checkpointer, and BOTH
 `:commit` and `:hold` durably append to the real audit ledger
 (`store/append-ledger!`). Store has a `MemStore` and a `DatomicStore`
 (via `kotoba-lang/langchain-store`, no hand-rolled EDN-blob codec),
 proven equivalent by a shared store-contract test. A smaller, honest
 check count for this jurisdiction is a deliberate design choice, not
 a shortcut -- see README 'Why fewer checks'."}
